<br>
E.G.<br>
<br>
A lvl 4 mob has a max hit of 10... which means that we cannot see the frequency for all 20 different values of n in DB + n * DI. You need to choose a target who can hit for 20 distinct values.<br>
<br>
Arlina <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uarlinastarbright.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Arlina Starbright</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are Superior</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#FF0000>(6/17/02 11:28:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1242.topic&index=133>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   the random range</span><hr size=1> We can deduce some things simply from the form of the current theory for how damage is done:<br>
<br>
I.E.<br>
<br>
damage = DB + round(n * DI)<br>
<br>
Where n is a uniform random integer (it has a flat graph over some range) minus some number that is a combination of your AC, mob's ATK, and possibly other factors, and is clamped into the range 1 .. 20.<br>
<br>
Given the hit distribution, one can determine what the range is. For instance, if a Krup Knight hits you for minimum damage 20% of the time and hits you for maximum 8% of the time, that would mean that:<br>
<br>
n = random[1 .. 25] - 4 = random[-3 .. 21]<br>
<br>
Knowing the sum of the frequencies of hits for min &amp; max can let us determine the range:<br>
[pre]<br>
range   min% + max%<br>
20        10.0%<br>
21        14.3%<br>
22        18.2%<br>
23        21.7%<br>
24        25.0%<br>
25        28.0%<br>
26        30.8%<br>
27        33.3%<br>
[/pre]<br>
<br>
Interestingly, all the parses I've seen of an enchanter tanking have had min% + max% near 27%, rarely near 25 or 30%... so it is feasible that the range is a constant 25 across all mobs. I don't have access to many melee tanking parses, so I don't know.<br>
<br>
<br>
Also, you would only see an increase in your tanking ability when you increase your AC far enough to shift the range down one unit... so that n = random[-3 .. 21] instead of n = random[-2 .. 22]. This would explain why there's the hypothesis of there being caps on AC, since you wouldn't see any benefit from adding AC until you reached a certain point.<br>
<br>
<br>
However, I think it's probable that the formula isn't quite so simple... but if it is, it wouldn't take too much to finish off the job and explain a lot of things.<br>
<br>
